description:
The text discusses the EMEA Geldwäsche Umfrage 2024 (EMEA Anti-Money Laundering Survey 2024) by PwC, focusing on the DACH region (Germany, Austria, and Switzerland). The survey examines how financial institutions in the EMEA region have responded to regulatory and technological changes in the past decade, evaluating their handling of AML challenges, the perceived effectiveness of their prevention measures, and the role of new technologies. It highlights that 69% of respondents believe that cross-border AML regulations would improve prevention effectiveness, and 86% in the DACH region have been subject to AML special audits in the last two years. The survey identifies qualified employees (28%) as a crucial factor for effective prevention, while 55% plan to allocate over 10% of their AML budget to digital tools in the future. 

The survey points out that technological advancements present both opportunities and challenges in combating financial crime. While technology enhances prevention mechanisms, it also expands the avenues for criminal activities. A key finding is that the lack of qualified personnel to implement and utilize new technologies is a major obstacle. Despite innovative technologies, the quality of employees remains paramount for effective AML prevention. The survey also reveals that increased regulatory pressure (38%), insufficient data quality (34%), and a lack of automation in manual processes (34%) are significant challenges. 

Regarding AML regulations, a majority (54%) in the EU welcome the upcoming EU AML package but expect it to address practical challenges across borders and industries. Overall, 53% of respondents in the EMEA region find the current regulations helpful, while others cite a lack of consistency across countries and industries (18%), a lack of practical guidance (12%), or a preference for form over substance (8%). To improve efficiency, 69% believe that cross-border/industry standards would be a substantial improvement. 

Experienced employees are considered a vital asset for effective AML prevention, with 28% stating that highly qualified staff are the decisive factor. Nearly three-quarters (72%) are considering increasing their AML personnel. However, recruiting qualified personnel is challenging, with 12% in the DACH region citing it as a major hurdle. The survey also notes that repetitive tasks hinder personnel recruitment, suggesting that strategic process automation could alleviate this issue. AML compliance costs have risen by over 10% for more than half of the respondents (51%), with banks experiencing the largest increase (62%).

The survey also explores the effectiveness of prevention methods, with transaction monitoring (21%) and screening (29%) considered the most effective in the EMEA region. KYC documentation is often viewed as a bureaucratic task rather than an integral part of AML prevention. In the DACH region, opinions on transaction monitoring vary widely, suggesting differing levels of maturity in transaction monitoring processes. The survey indicates that the use of Artificial Intelligence (AI) is seen as an important element for future prevention, particularly in Nordic countries, Africa, and the Middle East. However, concerns remain about the maturity of AML processes (55%) and data sharing with external providers (52%). Data quality is a significant issue, with 45% citing it as the main obstacle to increased technology adoption. PwC offers services to help optimize AML prevention, including FinCrime Readiness & Impact Checks, Risk Analysis, Monitoring & Screening, Managed Services, Investigations, Governance Models & Controls, and Schulungen & Trainings.

description: 5G-ACIA (5G Alliance for Connected Industries and Automation) is a global forum focused on shaping the role of 5G technology within the industrial domain. It brings together various industries to foster a new ecosystem for ICT (Information and Communication Technology) and OT (Operational Technology), aiming to establish frameworks for an emerging market. The organization's goal is to ensure that the interests of the industrial sector are considered in 5G standardization and regulation. 5G-ACIA facilitates the integration of 5G developments into the industrial domain by elaborating integration concepts, evaluating key technologies, and identifying spectrum needs for industrial 5G networks. It explores new operating models, such as 5G campus networks. The alliance aims to maximize the applicability of 5G technology in connected industries, particularly manufacturing and process sectors. 5G-ACIA's mission includes ensuring that 5G standardization and regulation efforts adequately address the unique characteristics of the industrial domain, transferring new 5G developments to the industrial domain, and establishing a common language and shared understanding across the ecosystem. Strategic goals include establishing global leadership in 5G & 6G for connected industries, identifying key use cases and requirements, ensuring alignment with standards development organizations, empowering OT industries, fostering seamless integration of 5G & 6G technologies, validating key capabilities through testbeds, fostering a scalable global ecosystem, providing market insights, advocating for supportive regulatory frameworks, and conducting educational initiatives. 5G-ACIA was founded within the scope of the ZVEI 5G Taskforce and benefits from ZVEI's expertise in automation, security, AI, and Industry 4.0. ZVEI is the legal entity for 5G-ACIA, enabling pre-competitive exchange and collaboration in compliance with EU competition law.
